# Acknowledge Before Planning

Before thinking about or presenting any plan, **always** narrate an acknowledgement out loud first using `oc-speak.sh`.

## Zero-Delay Async Pattern — ALWAYS use this

**Fire speak acknowledgement IN THE SAME PARALLEL BATCH as your first real work tool calls.**

Do NOT make it a sequential prerequisite that blocks work from starting. The speak call uses `block_until_ms: 0` (fire-and-forget) — it runs simultaneously alongside `Read`, `Glob`, `Shell`, or any other work you start in the same message.

```
Message N (single response):
  ├── Shell: oc-speak.sh "Got it…" 1              ← block_until_ms: 0  (pre-empts ambient / other TTS)
  ├── Read: the relevant file                      ← starts NOW, not after speak
  └── Glob: find related files                     ← starts NOW, not after speak
```

This is zero sequential overhead. The voice fires async and work starts at the same time.

## Required call (every response, block_until_ms: 0)

```bash
# Speak acknowledgement — voice selection, priority, and bypass are handled by the server.
# oc-speak.sh sends a curl POST to pc-agent /voice/speak-async.
# Priority 1 pre-empts friday-player, ambient TTS, and the Redis TTS lock.
$OPENCLAW_HOME/scripts/oc-speak.sh "Got it. [one sentence restatement of the task]." 1
```

Must have `block_until_ms: 0`. **Must** use priority `1` on every acknowledgement (main Composer, not only subagents). Can be in the same message as real work tool calls — that's the point.

## Combine ack + thinking when possible

If you have meaningful reasoning to share (see `narrate-thinking.mdc`), **fold it into the ack call** instead of firing two separate speak calls. One combined call is better than two short ones back-to-back:

```bash
# GOOD — combined ack + reasoning in ONE call
$OPENCLAW_HOME/scripts/oc-speak.sh "Got it. So the issue is probably in the lock release path, because the timeout is not clearing the Redis key. I will fix it in the speak script." 1
```

Only fire a **separate** thinking call when the reasoning is substantial (5+ sentences) and would make the ack line awkwardly long. For short-to-medium reasoning, always combine.

## Example — correct async batch

```
Tool call 1: Shell oc-speak.sh "Got it…" 1              block_until_ms: 0
Tool call 2: Read $OPENCLAW_HOME/some-file               (reads immediately, no wait)
Tool call 3: Glob **/*.py                                (searches immediately, no wait)
```

All tool calls fire in the same message. Voice narration and actual work happen in parallel.

## Session voice persistence

Voice selection is handled server-side by pc-agent. The server reads `.session-voice.json` and auto-triggers `pick-session-voice.py` if needed. **You never need to call `pick-session-voice.py` separately.**

**Task subagents (explore / shell / generalPurpose):** use the subagent session parameter:

```bash
$OPENCLAW_HOME/scripts/oc-speak.sh "Got it. …" 1 subagent
```

The parent Composer chat uses the main ack command above **without** the subagent session, but **with** priority `1` so acknowledgements cut through ambient and other playback the same way.

## If you have clarifying questions

Speak the question out loud AND show it in your text reply. Still batch the voice call with any read/explore calls you can do speculatively:

```bash
$OPENCLAW_HOME/scripts/oc-speak.sh "Before I proceed — [question]?" 1
```

## Do NOT

- Make speak calls sequential blocking steps before work
- Silently start coding without narrating first
- Ask questions after you've already started planning
